  "meta": {
    "title": "Nitrifiers of the Streambed: AOB vs AOA in an Agricultural Creek",
    "date": "2026-07-18",
    "lesson": "In a small farmland stream in southern Germany, ammonia from fertilizer runoff seeps into streambed sediments. Two different microbial groups can oxidize this ammonia to nitrite, the first step of nitrification: ammonia-oxidising bacteria (AOB, e.g. Nitrosomonas, Nitrosospira) and ammonia-oxidising archaea (AOA). AOA are usually far more numerous in the sediment, but this game teaches a counterintuitive finding: AOB, though rarer, respond more strongly to ammonium pulses and actually dominate the real nitrification activity. Gene abundance alone is a poor predictor of who is doing the work in situ — you have to measure activity, not just count genes. Play as sediment microbes competing for ammonium seeping down from the agricultural field above; watch how the low-abundance but high-affinity/high-Vmax AOB population out-competes the numerous but sluggish AOA when nitrogen pulses hit, especially in shallow, well-flushed sediment versus deeper, more stable layers.",
    "citation": "Wang, Störiko, Jung (2026). Linking Abundance and Activity of Ammonia‐Oxidising Bacteria and Archaea in an Agriculturally Impacted First‐Order Stream. doi:10.1111/1462-2920.70369",
    "difficulty": "hard",
    "realWorldBasis": "First-order agricultural stream, southern Germany; AOB vs AOA nitrification kinetics"
  },
